default5default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFuture Resilience across the London Airport Systemdefault&#xa0;default5.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the key issues that will need to be addressed when 
defaultlooking at future resilience acr
defaultoss the London airport system 
defaultis
default Heathrow’s over scheduling
default of flights in the key winter
default months. In order to ensure that the best plans are in place to deal with 
defaultany 
defaultadverse weather Gatwick believes that it is necessary for Heathrow to put in place a more robust plan to ensure future resilience. 
default5.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn January this year Gatwick called on the Government to bring together London’s three main airports to work out how we can 
defaultbest avoid significant numbers of business and leisure passengers being impacted by large numbers of pre-emptive flight cancellations at Heathrow. This was seen following the 
defaultunacceptable and damaging
default 
defaultnumber of 
defaultcancellations at Heathrow when London experie
defaultnced light amounts of snow early in 2013. 
default5.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn the long-term, we believe that following the recommendations of 
defaultthe Airports Commission
default this issue will be addressed with a new runway in the South East creating greater capacity. However it is not likely that 
defaultthis will be delivered until the mid-2020s 
defaultat the earliest 
defaultand as such we believe that further measures need to be taken by Heathrow to ensure that such disruptions are limited. Gatwick put forward a number of proposals in a letter to the Secretary of Stat
defaulte in January this year
default. (
defaultAppen
defaultd
defaultix 
defaultC
default)
default. 
default5.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn order to ensure that we can limit the impact of adverse weather
default we
default believe that Heathrow will need to stop their current approach to overscheduling during December, January and February. We believe it is vital for Heathrow to declare 
defaulta level of capacity it can cope with in winter conditions. The additional flights t
defaulthen, 
defaultfor those three months, would be able to
default move to Gatwick and Stansted. As a result there would be better use of the existing capacity at our London airports, safety would be enhanced and passengers will not have to panic every time it snows. 
defaultAs a result we
default are calling on the a
defaultirports and airlines 
defaultto
default work together to make this happen.
default5.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultClearly in extreme winter weather conditions a level of disruption at airports is to be expected but we should all be able to be open for business when confronted with normal winter weather conditions as 
defaultwas experienced in January of this year. 
